{"cursor":"6310","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name =Constance of Castile title = Duchess of Lancaster image =\n| Dukeoflancaster.jpg spouse = John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster issue =\n| Catherine, Queen of Castile house = House of Burgundy (by birth) House of\n| Lancaster (by marriage) father = Peter of Castile mother = MarÃ­a de Padilla\n| birth_date = 1354 birth_place = Castrojeriz, Castile death_date = death_place\n| = Leicester Castle, Leicestershire place of burial = Newark Abbey, Leicester\n| religion =Roman Catholicism }}\n'Constance of Castile' (1354 – 24 March 1394) was claimant of the\nCastilian throne after the death of her father Peter the Cruel, her mother being\nMarÃ­a de Padilla, whom Peter had secretly married but was then forced to\nrepudiate, only to keep her as a mistress. She married, at Roquefort, near\nBordeaux, Guienne, on 21 September 1371, John of Gaunt, 1st Duke of Lancaster,\nthird son of Edward III of England and Philippa of Hainault, as his second wife.\nHer younger sister, Infanta Isabella, married Edmund of Langley, 1st Duke of\nYork, the fourth son of King Edward III and Queen Philippa.\n\nOn 9 February 1372 Constance made a ceremonial entry into London as Queen of\nCastile, accompanied by Edward, the Black Prince, and an escort of English and\nCastilian retainers and London dignitaries. Crowds lined the streets to see her\nas she processed to the Savoy Palace in the Strand where she was ceremonially\nreceived by her husband, who had proclaimed himself King of Castile and LeÃ³n on\n29 January. Jonathan Sumption, Divided Houses: The Hundred Years War III\n(Faber & Faber, 2009), p. 122.\n\nThis was the way for Gaunt to obtain a kingdom of his own (he had also pursued\nScotland), as his nephew Richard II and the descendants of his brother Lionel of\nAntwerp, 1st Duke of Clarence stood between him and the Crown of England. John\nof Gaunt claimed the title of King of Castile [[jure uxoris]], and insisted that\nEnglish nobles address him as \"my lord of Spain\", but was unsuccessful in his\nattempts to obtain the crown. Their daughter Catherine of Lancaster was married\nto the king of the TrastÃ¡mara line, Henry III of Castile, thus uniting these two\nrival claims.\n\nConstance died at Leicester Castle and was buried at Newark Abbey, Leicester.\n","linknr":191,"url":"Infanta_Constance_of_Castile","recorded":1375075285,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Constance_of_Castile,_Duchess_of_Lancaster&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Constance_of_Castile,_Duchess_of_Lancaster&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Constance_of_Castile,_Duchess_of_Lancaster","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Infanta_Constance_of_Castile&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:Translation_to_english_arrow.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Translation_to_english_arrow.svg/50px-Translation_to_english_arrow.svg.png","//es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constanza_de_Castilla_(1354-1394)","//es.wikipedia.org/wiki/","http://translate.google.com/translate?&u=http%3A%2F%2Fes.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FConstanza+de+Castilla+%281354-1394%29&sl=es&tl=en","/wiki/Talk:Constance_of_Castile,_Duchess_of_Lancaster","/wiki/Wikipedia:Copying_within_W